<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="19" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,1190,1791]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1262,1287]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Remarks.</emphasis>
Aside from 
<taxonomicName authority="Gili, Lopez-Gonzalez &amp; Bouillon, 2006" authorityName="Gili, Lopez-Gonzalez &amp; Bouillon" authorityYear="2006" box="[468,1123,1262,1287]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Corynidae" genus="Sarsia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="medelae">
<emphasis box="[468,644,1262,1287]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Sarsia medelae</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Gili, J. M. &amp; Lopez-Gonzalez, P. J. &amp; Bouillon, J." box="[656,1123,1262,1287]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="624 - 631" refId="ref42397" refString="Gili, J. M., Lopez-Gonzalez, P. J. &amp; Bouillon, J. (2006) A new Antarctic association: the case of the hydroid Sarsia medelae (new sp.) associated with gorgonians. Polar Biology, 29 (7), 624 - 631. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 00300 - 005 - 0098 - x" type="journal article" year="2006">Gili, López-González &amp; Bouillon, 2006</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, a non-parasitic mesobiont inhabiting calcaxonian gorgonians in the Weddell Sea (
<bibRefCitation author="Gili, J. M. &amp; Lopez-Gonzalez, P. J. &amp; Bouillon, J." box="[774,952,1298,1323]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="624 - 631" refId="ref42397" refString="Gili, J. M., Lopez-Gonzalez, P. J. &amp; Bouillon, J. (2006) A new Antarctic association: the case of the hydroid Sarsia medelae (new sp.) associated with gorgonians. Polar Biology, 29 (7), 624 - 631. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 00300 - 005 - 0098 - x" type="journal article" year="2006">
Gili 
<emphasis box="[827,884,1298,1323]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">et al.</emphasis>
2006
</bibRefCitation>
), very few reports of the family 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Johnston" authorityYear="1836" box="[1319,1436,1298,1323]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Corynidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="family">Corynidae</taxonomicName>
exist for Antarctic waters, most of which could not be assigned to species level with enough solid grounds. 
<bibRefCitation author="Hickson, S. J. &amp; Gravely, F. H." pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="1 - 34" refId="ref42832" refString="Hickson, S. J. &amp; Gravely, F. H. (1907) Coelenterata. II. Hydroid zoophytes. National Antarctic Expedition (S. S. Discovery) 1901 - 1904, Natural History, 3, 1 - 34." type="journal article" year="1907">Hickson &amp; Gravely (1907)</bibRefCitation>
mentioned an undeterminable immature 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Johnston" authorityYear="1836" box="[834,950,1370,1395]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Corynidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="family">Corynidae</taxonomicName>
from McMurdo Sound (Ross Sea). Later, 
<bibRefCitation author="Stepanjants, S. D." box="[151,360,1406,1431]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="1 - 200" refId="ref47101" refString="Stepanjants, S. D. (1979) Hydroids of the antarctic and subantarctic waters. In: Biological results of the Soviet Antarctic Expedition, 6. Issledovaniya Fauny Morei, 20, 1 - 200. [in Russian]" type="journal article" year="1979">Stepanjants (1979)</bibRefCitation>
reported 
<taxonomicName authority="(M. Sars, 1835)" authorityName="M. Sars" authorityYear="1835" baseAuthorityName="M. Sars" baseAuthorityYear="1835" box="[467,822,1406,1431]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Corynidae" genus="Sarsia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="tubulosa">
<emphasis box="[467,641,1406,1431]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Sarsia tubulosa</emphasis>
(M. Sars, 1835)
</taxonomicName>
(as 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="M. Sars" baseAuthorityYear="1835" box="[868,1052,1406,1431]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Corynidae" genus="Coryne" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="tubulosa">
<emphasis box="[868,1052,1406,1431]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Coryne tubulosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) from the Davis Sea, although her Antarctic material was infertile. Recently, Peña Cantero 
<emphasis box="[796,854,1442,1467]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">et al.</emphasis>
(2013) described the early formation of tetraradial canals on reared polyps under laboratory conditions, which let them to assign their material to genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lesson" authorityYear="1843" box="[1306,1378,1479,1502]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Corynidae" genus="Sarsia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1306,1378,1479,1502]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Sarsia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with confidence, although no species could be attributed. These authors pointed out that their material might be conspecific with those previous records mentioned above. Material examined here might be also conspecific, but the absence of gonophores precludes a proper assignment even at genus level. Further research is needed regarding the corynids from the Southern Ocean.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="19" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,1190,1791]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,513,1658,1683]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Ecology and distribution.</emphasis>
Similar specimens were found at depths between three (
<bibRefCitation author="Stepanjants, S. D." pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="1 - 200" refId="ref47101" refString="Stepanjants, S. D. (1979) Hydroids of the antarctic and subantarctic waters. In: Biological results of the Soviet Antarctic Expedition, 6. Issledovaniya Fauny Morei, 20, 1 - 200. [in Russian]" type="journal article" year="1979">
Stepanjants 1979, as 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="M. Sars" baseAuthorityYear="1835" box="[151,336,1694,1719]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Corynidae" genus="Coryne" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="tubulosa">
<emphasis box="[151,336,1694,1719]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Coryne tubulosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</bibRefCitation>
) and 
<quantity box="[399,455,1695,1719]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" unit="m" value="40.0">40 m</quantity>
(Peña Cantero 
<emphasis box="[626,682,1694,1719]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">et al.</emphasis>
2013, as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lesson" authorityYear="1843" box="[787,858,1695,1718]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Corynidae" genus="Sarsia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[787,858,1695,1718]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Sarsia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp.); present material collected from 
<quantity box="[1275,1390,1694,1719]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.77" metricValueMax="2.87" metricValueMin="0.67" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" unit="m" value="177.0" valueMax="287.0" valueMin="67.0">
67– 
<specimenCount box="[1316,1390,1694,1719]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" type="generic">287 m</specimenCount>
</quantity>
. All the previous records of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lesson" authorityYear="1843" box="[423,494,1731,1754]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Corynidae" genus="Sarsia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[423,494,1731,1754]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Sarsia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. originate from East 
<collectingCountry box="[774,891,1730,1755]" name="Antarctica" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Antarctica</collectingCountry>
(see Peña Cantero 
<emphasis box="[1115,1173,1730,1755]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">et al.</emphasis>
2013). Present finding constitutes the first evidence of this undetermined corynid from West 
<collectingCountry box="[933,1050,1766,1791]" name="Antarctica" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Antarctica</collectingCountry>
and the Weddell Sea.
</paragraph>
